# Mojo variadic schema template pattern

Use this pattern when a model/schema can be expressed as a compile-time list of
field template types and runtime values should derive from that same list. This
is a non-reflection alternative for small typed schemas: the schema is the type
parameter pack, and runtime storage follows the pack.

## Shape

Define leaf templates that expose their runtime value type and any per-leaf
serialization or validation:

```mojo
trait SchemaLeaf:
    comptime Value: Copyable & Defaultable & ImplicitlyDestructible & Movable

    @staticmethod
    def field_name() -> String:
        ...

    @staticmethod
    def json_value(var value: Self.Value) raises -> JsonValue:
        ...
```

Define an object template that owns the variadic field pack:

```mojo
struct SchemaObject[
    name: StaticString,
    *Fields: SchemaLeaf,
]:
    @staticmethod
    def object_name() -> String:
        return String(Self.name)

    @staticmethod
    def field_count() -> Int:
        return len(Self.Fields)

    @staticmethod
    def field_name[i: Int]() -> String:
        return Self.Fields[i].field_name()
```

Define the runtime row directly from the same `name, *Fields` pack. Do not pass
a separate schema alias and the same fields again.

```mojo
comptime LeafValue[
    Leaf: SchemaLeaf,
]: Copyable & Defaultable & ImplicitlyDestructible & Movable = Leaf.Value

struct SchemaRow[
    name: StaticString,
    *Fields: SchemaLeaf,
](ImplicitlyDestructible, Movable):
    comptime Schema = SchemaObject[Self.name, *Self.Fields]
    comptime ValueTypes = TypeList.of[
        Trait=SchemaLeaf, *Self.Fields
    ]().map[
        ToTrait=Copyable & Defaultable & ImplicitlyDestructible & Movable,
        LeafValue,
    ]()

    var values: Tuple[*Self.ValueTypes]

    def __init__(out self):
        self.values = Tuple[*Self.ValueTypes]()

    def set[i: Int](mut self, var value: Self.ValueTypes[i]):
        comptime assert i >= 0 and i < len(Self.Fields)
        self.values[i] = value^

    @staticmethod
    def field_index[field_name: StaticString]() -> Int:
        comptime for i in range(len(Self.Fields)):
            comptime if String(field_name) == Self.Schema.field_name[i]():
                return i
        return -1

    def set_by_name[
        field_name: StaticString,
        Value: Copyable & Defaultable & ImplicitlyDestructible & Movable,
    ](
        mut self, var value: Value
    ) raises:
        comptime i = Self.field_index[field_name]()
        comptime assert i >= 0, "unknown schema field"
        self.set[i](rebind_var[Self.ValueTypes[i]](value^))
```

Then give call sites a single alias:

```mojo
comptime CatalogLineRow = SchemaRow[
    "catalog_line",
    YangString["title"],
    YangUInt16["units"],
]

var row = CatalogLineRow()
row.set_by_name["title"](String("mug"))
row.set_by_name["units"](3)
```

## Name-based setters

Use a compile-time field-name parameter when call sites should be resilient to
field order or more readable than numeric indexes. The method still compiles to
one typed slot assignment because `comptime for` resolves the matching field at
compile time.

Rules:

1. Make `field_name` a `StaticString` parameter, not a runtime `String`.
2. Use a `field_index[field_name]()` helper with `comptime for` over
   `len(Self.Fields)`.
3. Use `comptime if String(field_name) == Self.Schema.field_name[i]()` in that
   helper to find the slot.
4. In `set_by_name`, use `comptime assert i >= 0` so unknown names fail at
   compile time.
5. Forward through the typed index setter (`self.set[i](...)`) rather than
   duplicating storage assignment logic.
6. Bound the incoming `Value` enough for `rebind_var`:
   `Copyable & Defaultable & ImplicitlyDestructible & Movable`.
7. Let `Value` be inferred from the argument at the call site:
   `row.set_by_name["field"](value)`.

## Why

Avoid this duplicate shape:

```mojo
comptime CatalogLineSchema = SchemaObject[
    "catalog_line", YangString["title"], YangUInt16["units"]
]

var row = SchemaRow[
    CatalogLineSchema, YangString["title"], YangUInt16["units"]
]()
```

The fields appear twice and can drift. Instead, make the row derive its schema
and value tuple from one pack.

## Notes

1. This pattern avoids `std.reflection`; it uses explicit compile-time template
   parameters and `comptime for`.
2. If a trait boundary hides the concrete `Fields` pack, do not try to recover
   it through the trait. Carry the concrete pack on the row type and derive the
   schema alias internally.
3. For heterogeneous runtime values, map leaf templates to value types with a
   `TypeList.map[...]()` helper, then store `Tuple[*ValueTypes]`.
4. When a tuple element type needs to be passed back to its leaf template, use
   `rebind_var[Fields[i].Value](...)` if the compiler cannot prove the mapped
   tuple element and `Fields[i].Value` are identical.
5. Prefer a named row alias (`CatalogLineRow`) at call sites; it keeps the
   schema declaration single-source and construction short.
6. Prefer `set_by_name["field"](value)` for public examples and tests; keep
   `set[i](value)` available as the lower-level primitive.
